    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={2x^{2}-x-10}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-10\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(2.5,0\right), \left(-2,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={2x^{2}-x-10}</m>, and we have <m>y=-10</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-10)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={2x^{2}-x-10}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, notice that the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {2x^{2}-x-10} \\
   0 \amp = {2x^{2}-x-10} \\
   0 \amp = (2x - 5)(x + 2) \\
   2x - 5 = 0     \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x + 2 = 0 \\
   2x      = 5 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = -2 \\
   x          = 2.5 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = -2
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(2.5,0)</m> and <m>(-2,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
